      "id": "book-twenty-five-elisha-alyasa-prophetic-heir-successor-in-tandem-with-elijah-completing-his-work-upholding-god-s-oneness-against-canaanite-idolatry",
      "number": 3,
      "title": "Book Twenty-Five: Elisha (Alyasa‘): Prophetic Heir & Successor in Tandem with Elijah, Completing His Work & Upholding God’s Oneness against Canaanite Idolatry",
      "description": "As highlighted above, Elijah and Elisha—his Disciple and Prophetic Successor—worked together in a Prophetic tandem. For this reason, the last interludes of Elijah’s Prophetic Calling overlapped with the beginnings of Elisha’s own Mission.…",
      "sections": [
        {
          "id": "book-twenty-five-elisha-alyasa-prophetic-heir-successor-in-tandem-with-elijah-completing-his-work-upholding-god-s-oneness-against-canaanite-idolatry",
          "title": "Book Twenty-Five: Elisha (Alyasa‘): Prophetic Heir & Successor in Tandem with Elijah, Completing His Work & Upholding God’s Oneness against Canaanite Idolatry",
          "level": 3,
          "parentId": null,
          "content": "<p>As highlighted above, Elijah and Elisha—his Disciple and Prophetic Successor—worked together in a Prophetic tandem. For this reason, the last interludes of Elijah’s Prophetic Calling overlapped with the beginnings of Elisha’s own Mission. In Hebrew, Elisha (Hebrew: <em>Elîshā‘</em>; Arabic: <em>Alyasa‘</em>) means “My God is Salvation” (literally, <em>Elî Yeshā‘</em>). Both Prophets were closely associated with the Kingdom of Israel in Northern Palestine and the elimination of the Cult of the <em>Melqart Ba‘al </em>of Tyre. </p><p>     During that same generation, however, the Assyrian Empire had already risen to power in Northwestern Mesopotamia. It began to rapidly expand its borders systematically and would ultimately conquer and destroy the Kingdom of Israel, forcing its inhabitants into the Assyrian Captivity, which forever obliterated the Ten Tribes of Israel that had populated the North. Nevertheless, as we will see in what follows, God sent his Prophet Jonah to the Assyrians prior to the Assyrian Captivity to call them to the worship of God.</p><p>     Elisha is mentioned twice in the Qur’ān. Although his life-story is not told, God asserts that Elisha ranks among those whom He “favored above [all] the Worlds.” God says:</p><p>We bestowed upon [Abraham] Isaac and Jacob, each of whom We guided, just as We guided Noah [long] before [them], and among [Noah’s] seed, [We guided] David, Solomon, Job, Joseph, Moses, and Aaron: In this way do We reward [those who excel] as the Doers of Good. [And We guided] Zachariah, [his son] John, Jesus [Son of Mary], and Elijah, each of whom is among the righteous. [Likewise, We guided] Ishmael, <em>Elisha</em>, Jonah, and Lot—each [of these] We favored [with Prophecy] above [all] the Worlds. And from among their forefathers, their progeny, and their brothers [there are many whom We favored in this same fashion]: For We chose [them] and guided them unto a Straight Path. Such is God’s Guidance, He guides by it of His Servants whomever He wills (The Cattle, 6:84-88).</p><p>Elsewhere, God says in a similar vein:</p><p>Call to remembrance Our Servants Abraham, Isaac, and Jacob: All Men [endowed] with fullest strength [in worship] and perfect insight [into true Religion]. Truly, We purified them with [the blessing] of a purest attribute: [Constant] remembrance of the [ultimate] Abode [of the Hereafter]. Truly, in Our sight, they are among the chosen [Messengers and] the [finest of] the Elect. And call to remembrance Ishmael, <em>Elisha</em>, and Dhū-al-Kifl: Each [of them] is [truly] among the most excellent. This is [all] a [godly] reminder [in praising them], and for the reverent there shall surely be a beautiful Return [in the next Life]: Gardens of Eternity with Gates opened wide [for them] (Ṣād, 38:45-50).</p><p>Prophets and Messengers who are mentioned in the Qur’ān primarily by name—such as Elisha and Dhū-al-Kifl in particular—are elevated by their direct association with other Messengers, the greatness of whom we do know, and all of them, taken together, are then declared by such allusions to hold the highest Stations of universal renown with God by virtue of Prophecy, since they are among those upon whom God bestowed special Mercy and everlastingly Truthful renown (see Qur’ān, 19:50).</p><p>     According to the Biblical narrative, God appointed Elisha to bring the work of Elijah to completion, which meant the destruction of the House of Ahab in order “to avenge the blood of God’s Servants the Prophets and the blood of all the Servants of the Lord at the hand of Jezebel” (2 Kings, 9:6-7). In the Bible, Elijah was commanded to anoint Elisha as Prophet, and Elisha immediately attached himself to his master, serving him faithfully and witnessing with his own eyes Elijah’s Ascension up to the Heavens (1 Kings, 19:15-21). God gave the Prophet Elisha many Miracles as well as powerful political and social influence. As the Prophet Elijah had foretold, the perfidious Jezebel was herself abandoned in the end, ten years after the death of her husband King Ahab, and thrown down from her balcony—at the command of the new King Jehu (Hebrew: <em>Yēhû’</em>, meaning “the Lord is He”) (d. ca. 814 BCE), whom she was mocking. Jezebel was cast to the street below, where she was trampled to death by the soldiers’ horses and immediately eaten by dogs, so that no one could bury her (2 Kings, 9:10, 30-37; 10:10). King Jehu then set out to kill all the false prophets of the Tyrian <em>Ba‘al</em> and eradicate their followers, while all the remaining images and idols of the Tyrian god were burned (2 Kings, 10:19-26). After Elisha had extirpated the Cult of <em>Melqart</em> by fire and sword with the help of King Jehu, <em>Melqart</em>—the <em>Ba‘al</em> of Jezebel—would hardly be mentioned ever again, and never would his Cult gain a new foothold in Israel’s Northern Kingdom or the land of Judah to the South.  </p><p>     The Prophet Elisha died in 841 BCE. By the year 842 BCE—one year before his passing—the Cult of the Tyrian <em>Ba‘al</em>, which had finally been brought to an end, would never again entice the Children of Israel. Still, surprisingly, the<em> Be‘ālîm</em> remained a problem for the incorrigible Children of Israel for generations to come. Thus, although later Prophets like Amos (Hebrew: ‘<em>Āmôs</em>) (d. 740 CE) and Hosea (<em>Hôshēa‘</em>) (d. ca. 721) no longer had to expulse the Cult of the <em>Melqart Ba‘al</em>, they were still compelled to call both the Northern and Southern Kingdoms back to exclusive devotion to God and to purge the lingering rites associated with other Canaanite <em>Be‘ālîm</em>. Despite sustained Prophetic efforts, these reforms proved incomplete prior to the Assyrian and Babylonian Exiles. Certain Hypocrites among the Children of Israel would continually return to these false gods in one region or another and even place their images and idols in their private households for personal worship. Thus, paradoxically, it would only be after the Exile that all the <em>Be‘ālîm</em> were removed forever from the worship of the Children of Israel, and the words of the Prophet Hosea were finally fulfilled: “I [God] will take away the names of the <em>Be‘ālîm </em>from the mouth [of Israel], and they shall no longer be remembered by that name” (Hosea, 2:17). <a href=\"/v/15/book-twenty-five-elisha-alyasa-prophetic-heir-successor-in-tandem-with-elijah-completing-his-work-upholding-god-s-oneness-against-canaanite-idolatry/web-extension\" class=\"web-extension-chip\" data-web-extension-link=\"true\" aria-label=\"Open web extension 3\">Web-Extension 3</a></p>",
          "pageReference": 11,
          "footnotes": []
        }
      ]
