              "content": "<p> The Syriac adjective “<em>mahaimanā</em>” used in the verse “<em>dhe neqūm Nebhīyā mahaimanā</em>” (1 Maccabees, 14:41) means faithful and trustworthy. It is closely related to the Arabic adjective <em>muhaiman</em> (guardian protector) that we have seen used as a description of the Qur’ān’s role in protecting all pre-Qur’ānic scripture. But the Syriac verbs <em>haimen</em> and <em>emen</em> are primarily used for belief like the Arabic verb <em>āmana</em>. The Septuagint uses the Greek expression “<em>Prophētēn pistòn</em>,” which essentially has the same force as the Syriac “trustworthy” (<em>mahaimanā</em>). The Septuagint, however, does not use the definite article, but Greek has broad and often non-restrictive rules regarding the use of the definite article. </p>",
              "sectionId": "dark-night-of-wrath-wickedness-prophecy-s-last-knell-among-the-children-of-israel"
